  "bib_entries": {
    "11082627": {
      "title": "A common haplotype in the complement regulatory gene factor H (HF1/CFH) predisposes individuals to age-related macular degeneration",
      "abstract": "Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is the most frequent cause of irreversible blindness in the elderly in developed countries. Our previous studies implicated activation of complement in the formation of drusen, the hallmark lesion of AMD. Here, we show that factor H (HF1), the major inhibitor of the alternative complement pathway, accumulates within drusen and is synthesized by the retinal pigmented epithelium. Because previous linkage analyses identified chromosome 1q25-32, which harbors the factor H gene (HF1/CFH), as an AMD susceptibility locus, we analyzed HF1 for genetic variation in two independent cohorts comprised of ≈900 AMD cases and 400 matched controls. We found association of eight common HF1 SNPs with AMD; two common missense variants exhibit highly significant associations (I62V, χ2 = 26.1 and P = 3.2 × 10-7 and Y402H, χ2 = 54.4 and P = 1.6 × 10-13). Haplotype analysis reveals that multiple HF1 variants confer elevated or reduced risk of AMD. One common at-risk haplotype is present at a frequency of 50% in AMD cases and 29% in controls [odds ratio (OR) = 2.46, 95% confidence interval (1.95-3.11)]. Homozygotes for this haplotype account for 24% of cases and 8% of controls [OR = 3.51, 95% confidence interval (2.13-5.78)]. Several protective haplotypes are also identified (OR = 0.44-0.55), further implicating HF1 function in the pathogenetic mechanisms underlying AMD. We propose that genetic variation in a regulator of the alternative complement pathway, when combined with a triggering event, such as infection, underlie a major proportion of AMD in the human population."
    },
    "42858171": {
      "title": "Three new polymorphisms in the human complement factor H gene and promoter region",
      "abstract": "Complement factor H has an important regulatory role in the activation and activity of the alternative pathway. It consists of a single polypeptide chain of 1211 amino acids, subdivided into 20 independently folding homologous domains known as short consensus repeats (SCRs) joined together like “beads on a string” (DiScipio 1992). It is encoded by a single gene of approximately 100 kilobases located on chromosome 1q32. The gene has been partially characterized over a region coding for SCRs 3–10 (McAleer et al. 1988, 1989). Over this region, with the exception of SCR 7, each SCR is coded for by a single exon. Recently, a family of human plasma proteins has been identified which are related structurally and immunologically to factor H, termed factor H like (FHL) when coded for by alternatively spliced transcripts of the factor H gene, or factor H-related (FHR) when transcribed from separate genes (Zipfel and Skerka 1994). Polymorphisms of neuraminidase-treated plasma factor H have been documented by isoelectric focusing in North American (Rodriguez de Cordoba 1985; Rodriguez de Cordoba and Rubinstein 1987) and Japanese populations (Nakamura et al 1990). It is proposed that the range of phenotypes in Caucasians are coded for by five codominant alleles, FH1–5, with a frequency of 0.685, 0.301, 0.006, 0.006, and 0.002, respectively, and in Japanese by four codominant alleles with frequencies of 0.490, 0.426, 0.010, and 0.001, respectively. The presence of a null allele with a frequency of 0.07 was postulated in the Japanese population, but paradoxically homozygotes still had approximately 50% plasma levels of factor H. A restriction fragment length polymorphism (Bgl II) has been identified within the gene, although sequence and position has not been elucidated (McAleer et al. 1987) and this may be intronic. A sequence polymorphism has been described in exon 7, representing a T/C substitution reflecting a tyrosine/histidine polymorphism, with frequencies of approximately 0.67 and 0.33, respectively (Day et al. 1988) and which could account for the two common isoforms. An individual from West Africa was found to have a polymorphism in exon 20, representing a T/ C substitution reflecting a serine/proline polymorphism (Meyer et al. 1995), although population frequencies were not quoted. We discovered two new polymorphisms in exons/SCRs 5 and 16 of the factor H gene and one in the promoter region involving an NF kappa-B responsive element. The polymorphisms were detected by single-stranded conformational polymorphism (SSCP) analysis of polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-generated fragments of genomic DNA (Fig. 1) according to standard protocols, and using intraexonic and promoter region primers as listed below (with annealing temperatures):"
    },
    "6946471": {
      "title": "Cloning and analysis of the human complement factor H gene promoter",
      "abstract": "The 5' flanking region of human factor H was cloned using nested polymerase chain reaction (PCR) and the promoter finder method. A total of 1.2 kb has been sequenced and a number of putative regulatory elements identified including glucocorticoid response elements cAMP responsive element, HTF-1, and acute phase signal sequences. A 717 b.p. fragment was cloned into a CAT reporter vector and transfected into HeLa cells. A series of truncations from the 5' end of this fragment were also cloned into the CAT vector. Analysis of CAT activity of the cell lysates showed that the region from -699 to +18 is likely to contain promoter elements for the factor H gene as it was able to drive transcription of the CAT gene."
    }
  },
